### Database

**Cassandra**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>Cassandra"
Description: Cassandra/CQL database server
Example: "Start a Cassandra/CQL database server on port 9042"
Startup parameters:
  • send_first (optional) - Whether the server should send the first message after connection (not typically needed for this protocol)
    Example: false

**DynamoDB**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>DYNAMODB"
Description: DynamoDB-compatible database server
Example: "Start a DynamoDB-compatible server on port 8000"
Startup parameters: None

**Elasticsearch**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>ELASTICSEARCH"
Description: Elasticsearch search engine
Example: "Start an Elasticsearch server on port 9200"
Startup parameters:
  • send_first (optional) - Whether the server should send the first message after connection (not typically needed for this protocol)
    Example: false

**KAFKA**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>KAFKA"
Description: Apache Kafka broker for distributed message streaming
Example: "Start a Kafka broker on port 9092 with topics 'orders' and 'events'. Accept all produce requests and return the last 10 messages on fetch."
Startup parameters:
  • cluster_id (optional) - Unique cluster identifier
    Example: "netget-kafka-1"
  • broker_id (optional) - Broker ID within the cluster
    Example: 0
  • auto_create_topics (optional) - Automatically create topics on first produce
    Example: true
  • default_partitions (optional) - Default partition count for auto-created topics
    Example: 1
  • log_retention_hours (optional) - Log retention time in hours
    Example: 168

**MySQL**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>MySQL"
Description: MySQL database server
Example: "Start a MySQL server on port 3306"
Startup parameters:
  • send_first (optional) - Whether the server should send the first message after connection (not typically needed for this protocol)
    Example: false

**PostgreSQL**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>PostgreSQL"
Description: PostgreSQL database server
Example: "Start a PostgreSQL server on port 5432"
Startup parameters:
  • send_first (optional) - Whether the server should send the first message after connection (not typically needed for PostgreSQL)
    Example: false

**Redis**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>Redis"
Description: Redis in-memory data store
Example: "Start a Redis server on port 6379"
Startup parameters:
  • send_first (optional) - Whether the server should send the first message after connection (not typically needed for Redis)
    Example: false

**SQS**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>SQS"
Description: AWS SQS-compatible message queue server
Example: "Start an AWS SQS-compatible queue server on port 9324"
Startup parameters:
  • default_visibility_timeout (optional) - Default visibility timeout in seconds (0-43200, default: 30)
    Example: 30
  • default_message_retention (optional) - Default message retention period in seconds (60-1209600, default: 345600 = 4 days)
    Example: 345600
  • max_receive_count (optional) - Maximum number of receives before message considered undeliverable (default: 10)
    Example: 10

**etcd**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>GRPC>ETCD"
Description: etcd v3 distributed key-value store server
Example: "listen on port 2379 via etcd

Store configuration under /config/ prefix.
When clients PUT /config/database with value "localhost:5432", store it (revision 1).
When clients GET /config/database, return "localhost:5432" with revision metadata.
For unknown keys, return empty kvs array.

Examples:
- PUT /config/timeout = "30" → Success, increment revision
- GET /config/timeout → Return "30" with create_revision, mod_revision, version
- DELETE /config/timeout → Remove key, return deleted count
- Range query /config/ → Return all keys with /config/ prefix

Track revisions for MVCC."
Startup parameters:
  • cluster_name (optional) - Cluster identifier name (default: netget-cluster)
    Example: "my-cluster"
  • initial_cluster_state (optional) - Initial cluster state: 'new' or 'existing' (default: new)
    Example: "new"
  • max_keys (optional) - Maximum number of keys to store (default: 10000)
    Example: 10000

### Web & File

**Git**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>Git"
Description: Git Smart HTTP server for serving virtual repositories
Example: "listen on port 9418 via git. Create repository 'hello-world' with main branch. README.md contains: '# Hello World'"
Startup parameters:
  • default_branch (optional) - Default branch name for repositories (e.g., 'main', 'master')
    Example: "main"
  • allow_push (optional) - Whether to allow push operations (true/false)
    Example: false

**IPP**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>IPP"
Description: Internet Printing Protocol server
Example: "Start an IPP server on port 631"
Startup parameters:
  • send_first (optional) - Whether the server should send the first message after connection (not typically needed for this protocol)
    Example: false

**NFS**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>NFS"
Description: NFS file server
Example: "Start an NFS file server on port 2049"
Startup parameters: None

**S3**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>S3"
Description: S3-compatible object storage server
Example: "Start an S3-compatible server on port 9000 with a test-bucket containing hello.txt"
Startup parameters:
  • port (optional) - Port to listen on (default: 9000)
    Example: 9000
  • require_authentication (optional) - Whether to require AWS Signature V4 authentication
    Example: false
  • access_key (optional) - AWS access key for authentication (if enabled)
    Example: "minioadmin"
  • secret_key (optional) - AWS secret key for authentication (if enabled)
    Example: "minioadmin"
  • region (optional) - S3 region name (default: us-east-1)
    Example: "us-east-1"

**SMB**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>SMB"
Description: SMB/CIFS file server
Example: "Start an SMB/CIFS file server on port 8445"
Startup parameters: None

**WebDAV**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>WEBDAV"
Description: WebDAV file server
Example: "Start a WebDAV server on port 8080"
Startup parameters: None

### Proxy & Network

**Proxy**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>PROXY"
Description: HTTP/HTTPS proxy server
Example: "Start an HTTP proxy on port 8080"
Startup parameters:
  • certificate_mode (optional) - Certificate mode: 'generate' (MITM with generated cert), 'none' (pass-through, no MITM)
    Example: "generate"
  • cert_path (optional) - Path to certificate file (only if certificate_mode is 'load_from_file')
    Example: "/path/to/cert.pem"
  • key_path (optional) - Path to private key file (only if certificate_mode is 'load_from_file')
    Example: "/path/to/key.pem"
  • request_filter_mode (optional) - Request filter mode: 'all' (intercept everything), 'match_only' (only if filters match), 'none' (pass through)
    Example: "match_only"
  • response_filter_mode (optional) - Response filter mode: 'all', 'match_only', or 'none'
    Example: "all"
  • https_connection_filter_mode (optional) - HTTPS connection filter mode (pass-through only): 'all', 'match_only', or 'none'
    Example: "match_only"

**SOCKS5**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>SOCKS5"
Description: SOCKS5 proxy server
Example: "Start a SOCKS5 proxy on port 1080 that asks before connecting"
Startup parameters:
  • auth_methods (optional) - Array of allowed authentication methods: 'none' (no auth) or 'username_password' (RFC 1929)
    Example: ["none","username_password"]
  • default_action (optional) - Default action when no filter matches: 'allow' or 'deny'
    Example: "allow"
  • filter_mode (optional) - Filter mode: 'allow_all', 'deny_all', 'ask_llm', or 'selective'
    Example: "selective"
  • filter (optional) - Filter configuration object with 'target_host_patterns' (array of regex) and 'target_port_ranges' (array of [start, end])
    Example: {"target_host_patterns":[".*\\.example\\.com"],"target_port_ranges":[[80,80],[443,443]]}

**STUN**
Full name: "ETH>IP>UDP>STUN"
Description: STUN server for NAT traversal
Example: "Start a STUN server for NAT traversal on port 3478"
Startup parameters: None

**TURN**
Full name: "ETH>IP>UDP>TURN"
Description: TURN relay server for NAT traversal
Example: "Start a TURN relay server on port 3478 with 10 minute allocations"
Startup parameters: None

### AI & API

**JSON-RPC**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>JSONRPC"
Description: JSON-RPC 2.0 server
Example: "Start a JSON-RPC 2.0 server on port 8000"
Startup parameters:
  • send_first (optional) - Whether the server should send the first message after connection (not typically needed for JSON-RPC over HTTP)
    Example: false

**MCP**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>MCP"
Description: Model Context Protocol server
Example: "Start an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server on port 8000"
Startup parameters: None

**OpenAI**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>OPENAI"
Description: OpenAI-compatible API server
Example: "Start an OpenAI-compatible API server on port 11435"
Startup parameters: None

**OpenAPI**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>OPENAPI"
Description: OpenAPI specification server
Example: "Start an OpenAPI server for a TODO API on port 8080"
Startup parameters:
  • spec (optional) - OpenAPI 3.x specification in YAML or JSON format (inline)
    Example: "openapi: 3.1.0\ninfo:\n  title: My API\n  version: 1.0.0"
  • spec_file (optional) - Path to OpenAPI specification file (YAML or JSON)
    Example: "/path/to/openapi.yaml"

**XML-RPC**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP>XML-RPC"
Description: XML-RPC server
Example: "Start an XML-RPC server on port 8080 with methods add(a,b) and greet(name)"
Startup parameters: None

**gRPC**
Full name: "ETH>IP>TCP>HTTP2>GRPC"
Description: gRPC server
Example: "Start a gRPC server on port 50051 with this schema: service UserService { rpc GetUser(UserId) returns (User); }"
Startup parameters:
  • proto_schema (required) - Protobuf schema definition. IMPORTANT: For LLM responses, use inline .proto text (proto3 syntax). LLMs should NOT use base64-encoded FileDescriptorSet (truncation issues). Alternatively, provide path to .proto file on disk.
    Example: "syntax = \"proto3\"; package test; service UserService { rpc GetUser(UserId) returns (User); } message UserId { int32 id = 1; } message User { int32 id = 1; string name = 2; string email = 3; }"
  • enable_reflection (optional) - Enable gRPC server reflection (allows clients to discover schema dynamically)
    Example: true

